The paper deals with learning Gaussian Graphical Models, which is a topic in machine learning and statistics. The paper uses information-theoretic arguments to provide a lower bound on the minimum number of samples necessary to perfectly identify the support of any multivariate normal distribution. This suggests that the paper is likely to be categorized under cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.IT (Information Theory). Additionally, the paper proposes algorithms for learning Gaussian Graphical Models, which involves computational aspects, making it relevant to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Finally, the paper's focus on sparse graphs and edge strength may also make it relevant to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
